SKILL|himalaya|"Himalaya CLI: IMAP/SMTP email from terminal."
STEP|1|`references/configuration.md` (config file setup + IMAP/SMTP authentication)
STEP|2|`references/message-composition.md` (MML syntax for composing emails)
STEP|3|Himalaya CLI installed (`himalaya --version` to verify)
STEP|4|A configuration file at `~/.config/himalaya/config.toml`
STEP|5|IMAP/SMTP credentials configured (password stored securely)
STEP|6|**Reading, listing, searching, moving, deleting** all work directly through the terminal tool
STEP|7|**Composing/replying/forwarding** — piped input (`cat << EOF \| himalaya template send`) is recommended for reliability. Interactive `$EDITOR` mode works with `pty=true` + background + process tool, b
STEP|8|Use `--output json` for structured output that's easier to parse programmatically
STEP|9|The `himalaya account configure` wizard requires interactive input — use PTY mode: `terminal(command="himalaya account configure", pty=true)`
STEP|10|Non-interactive (use this from Hermes)** — pipe the message via stdin:
STEP|11|Use `himalaya --help` or `himalaya <command> --help` for detailed usage.
STEP|12|Message IDs are relative to the current folder; re-list after folder changes.
STEP|13|For composing rich emails with attachments, use MML syntax (see `references/message-composition.md`).
STEP|14|Store passwords securely using `pass`, system keyring, or a command that outputs the password.
